05093nam a22006375i 9780231550703DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315507037 a10.7312/gilm194202doi  a(DE-B1597)642831  a(OCoLC)1344005673  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0720002bisacsh04a305.42223//eng/20220607eng1 aGilmore, Leigh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe #MeToo Effect :bWhat Happens When We Believe Women /cLeigh Gilmore. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b2 images: a Tweet and a Times magazine cover  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGender and Culture Series00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION The #MeToo Effect -- tI NARRATIVE ACTIVISM AND SURVIVOR TESTIMONY -- t1 THE #METOO EFFECT From He Said/She Said to Collective Witness -- t2 BUILDUP Survivors in Public, Trump, and the Women’s March -- t3 BREAKTHROUGH #MeToo Silence Breakers -- t4 BACKDROP Antirape Lineage from Harriet Jacobs to Tarana Burke -- t5 #METOO STRESS TEST The Kavanaugh Hearings -- tII NARRATIVE JUSTICE AND SURVIVOR READING -- t6 READING LIKE A SURVIVOR -- t7 #METOO STORYTELLING -- t8 CONSENT BEFORE AND AFTER #METOO -- tCONCLUSION Promising Young Women— What We Owe Survivors -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe #MeToo movement inspired millions to testify to the widespread experience of sexual violence. More broadly, it shifted the deeply ingrained response to women’s accounts of sexual violence from doubting all of them to believing some of them. What changed?Leigh Gilmore provides a new account of #MeToo that reveals how storytelling by survivors propelled the call for sexual justice beyond courts and high-profile cases. At a time when the cultural conversation was fixated on appeals to legal and bureaucratic systems, narrative activism—storytelling in the service of social change—elevated survivors as authorities. Their testimony fused credibility and accountability into the #MeToo effect: uniting millions of separate accounts into an existential demand for sexual justice and the right to be heard.Gilmore reframes #MeToo as a breakthrough moment within a longer history of feminist thought and activism. She analyzes the centrality of autobiographical storytelling in intersectional and antirape activism and traces how literary representations of sexual violence dating from antiquity intertwine with cultural notions of doubt, obligation, and agency. By focusing on the intersectional prehistory of #MeToo, Gilmore sheds light on how survivors have used narrative to frame sexual violence as an urgent problem requiring structural solutions in diverse global contexts. Considering the roles of literature and literary criticism in movements for social change, The #MeToo Effect demonstrates how “reading like a survivor” provides resources for activism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMeToo movement. 0aSexual harassment of women. 0aWomenxCrimes against. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Activism & Social Justice.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL0 cprintz978023119420